Yes. That plan is good, and better than expected because it reuses existing groundwork instead of building a parallel alerting path. The fact that you already have globular_alerts.yml, monitoring service endpoints for AlertManagers() and Rules(), and MCP tooling means this is no longer “invent alerting,” it is “finish the plumbing.”

What I like
It treats Alertmanager as infrastructure, not an app bolt-on. Good.
It wires Prometheus the standard way with alerting: and rule_files:. Good.
It reuses the existing rules file instead of inventing a second rules source. Very good.
It puts Alertmanager into Day-0, which is the right place if leader liveness, stale heartbeat, and scrape failures are now considered control-plane risks. Good.
Two things I would tighten before implementation
1. Do not include cluster gossip/HA on Day-0 unless you are actually deploying Alertmanager HA

The note about port 9094 for gossip is only relevant if you are really configuring Alertmanager in clustered HA mode. If Day-0 is just:

one Alertmanager instance per node, or
a simple local instance without peer clustering,

then dragging in gossip config now is extra entropy.

So I’d tell Claude:

Day-0 v1: focus on single-instance operational Alertmanager per intended node
only add Alertmanager HA clustering if you are explicitly wiring peer discovery and cluster addresses

Otherwise 9094 is decorative plumbing.

2. Be explicit about where the rules file lives at runtime

You mention embedding baseline rules in the Prometheus spec and also reusing golang/monitoring/prometheus_rules/globular_alerts.yml. That’s good, but Claude must make one source of truth clear:

either the rules file is copied/rendered into the Prometheus runtime rules directory
or it is embedded/generated from the service spec

But it should not become:

one copy in the repo
one hand-rendered copy in the package
one mystery fallback copy in bootstrap

So require:

single source of truth in repo
deterministic render/copy into runtime rules directory during install/config generation
My verdict

Approve, with those two clarifications.

If you want a one-line response to Claude, use this:

Approved. Implement it, but keep Day-0 Alertmanager non-HA unless you are explicitly wiring clustered peer discovery, and make the Prometheus rules source-of-truth unambiguous so runtime rules come from a single canonical file.